Comment: I played as Black in this unrated game against one of my teammates whom I found to be a strong 1700  player.  In the game, Black plays an interesting 9th move which defines a good portion of the game.  Late in the game, Black blunders away a winning position and with a second blunder loses the chance to draw.  The credit really goes to White though who played a nearly flawless game.

f5!? This, to me, is one of the defining moves of the game, intended to shut down the attack along the b1-h7 diagonal.  Yet, as my opponent pointed out to me after the game, g6 was probably objectively better as this weakens the a2-g8 diagonal which becomes a thorn in my side.

Here I made the decision to try to get my bishops to optimum locations as I thought the diagonals would probably be what would win or lose the game from this point.
Ideally, I would like to blockade the passed pawn with my dark squared bishop on d6 and get my light squared bishop to b5.
